The Hajj and Umrah contribute billions of dollars to the Saudi economy each year, in addition to being a sacred tradition. But there is an excellent chance that if COVID19 cases continue their trajectory, the Hajj will be cancelled. This is especially true since Mecca province is currently leading the country in the number of cases. Adding an influx of individuals from around the globe to contribute to the outbreak would be extremely unwise. Some quarters believe that the Saudis have done a good job of managing the crisis relative to many other countries, so it is difficult to comprehend that they would risk those gains by inviting citizens of other nations into the country.

New infections have been growing in Qatar for all of June 2020 so far at a rate above 10k in a 7-day trailing sum. So even if there was a strictly restricted Hajj limited to the Arabian peninsular, there is a gigantic risk that spread of the SARS-CoV-2 virus is promoted in an already very risky environment.

With Saudi covid cases still exploding we're basically on a knife edge waiting to see whether the Saudi govt puts a super-spreading event - even at 20% or fewer pilgrims - ahead of controlling the pandemic. Bearing in mind that Hajj consists of traveling widely around the Kingdom, only a domestic-only Hajj seems likely to me, and given the economic impact the pandemic is having in countries that have failed to control it, I think even that would be in doubt to a nation not culturally invested in allowing Hajj to go ahead for other reasons. As more nations suspend Hajj for 2020, I think the cultural price of allowing it to go ahead may start outweighing what Saudi currently still perceive as the benefits. Therefore staying high on cancellation, to balance out previous forecasts, though prepared to move.

Though low compared to its detected number of cases, Saudi has already experienced the highest number of deaths of any country in the GCC. Mecca is still under strict lockdown & a new phase of national lockdown to coincide with Eid was announced some days ago. With a spike in new cases over the last couple of days it seems likely more announcements including cancellation of the Hajj will follow. The question is therefore of political timing. While it seems unlikely that Saudi will drag out decision making as per Japan & the Olympics, there may be some advantage in allowing partially restricted business to continue as usual during Ramadan then announcing the cancellation immediately after Eid once the seasonal increase in spending is completed but in time to be seen to be protecting older generations in a culture where this is of great importance. This move would allow the government to consolidate the economic hit and potentially time the announcement of the cancellation to precede or coincide with the death spike that corresponds to the current rise in new cases, depending on the specific point of infection at which these cases are being detected. Since, as @cafebedouin has said, the pilgrimage begins in late June & resources spent preparing for it will be needlessly wasted unless it goes ahead, this factor is, again, pushing me towards anticipating a relatively early cancellation either at the end of May or the beginning of June.
